        content: 'The ALTA/NSPS Land Title Survey standards are jointly published by the American Land Title Association (ALTA) and the National Society of Professional Surveyors (NSPS). These standards establish the minimum requirements for surveys that will be used in conjunction with title insurance policies for commercial and residential real estate transactions. The current version, adopted February 23, 2021, replaced the 2016 standards and introduced several important changes including updated Table A items and revised positional tolerance requirements.\n\nALTA is a national trade association representing the title insurance industry, while NSPS is the professional organization representing licensed surveyors. Their collaboration ensures that the standards serve both the title insurance industry\'s need for reliable property information and the surveying profession\'s technical capabilities. The standards exist because title insurance underwriters need consistent, reliable survey information to assess risk when insuring property titles, and surveyors need clear guidance on what a title survey must include.\n\nThese standards apply specifically to "Land Title Surveys" — surveys ordered in connection with the issuance of title insurance. They do not apply to boundary surveys performed for other purposes such as fence line disputes, subdivision platting, or construction staking. A surveyor performing a boundary survey for a neighbor dispute would follow state minimum standards rather than the ALTA/NSPS standards unless specifically requested. However, because the ALTA/NSPS standards represent a high bar of practice, many surveyors use them as a reference even for non-title surveys.\n\nThe scope of an ALTA/NSPS survey goes well beyond simply locating boundary lines. The surveyor must research the current title commitment or title report, locate and identify improvements, easements, rights of way, evidence of utilities, and other features that affect the property. The survey must show the relationship between the boundaries and the improvements, and the surveyor must certify the survey to specific parties identified in the engagement. This comprehensive scope is what distinguishes a Land Title Survey from a simple boundary survey.\n\nWhen reviewing these standards during the exam, the document is organized into numbered sections. Sections 1 and 2 define the scope and request requirements. Section 3 covers the survey itself including research, fieldwork, and positional tolerances. Sections 4 and 5 address what must appear on the face of the survey plat and the certification language. Section 6 covers deliverables, and Section 7 addresses the Table A optional items. Understanding this organization helps you navigate the PDF quickly during timed exam questions.',
