        id: 'fs-std-alta-s2',
        type: 'concept',
        title: 'Table A Optional Items Walkthrough',
        content: 'Table A is perhaps the most frequently referenced portion of the ALTA/NSPS standards. It lists optional survey responsibilities that go beyond the minimum requirements. The client (or the client\'s lender or title company) selects which Table A items apply to a particular survey engagement. Each item adds scope — and typically cost — to the survey. Under the 2021 standards, there are 20 numbered Table A items (Items 1 through 20), some with lettered sub-items.\n\nItem 1 concerns monuments. The surveyor must set monuments at all major corners of the property if this item is selected. Without Item 1, the surveyor is only required to search for existing monuments and report what is found. Item 2 addresses addresses, and requires the surveyor to provide the street address of the property based on the best available information. Item 3 covers flood zone classification, requiring the surveyor to state the flood zone designation from FEMA flood maps and whether the property is located in a Special Flood Hazard Area. This is one of the most commonly requested items because lenders require flood zone information.\n\nItems 4 through 7 deal with building and site features. Item 4 relates to gross land area, requiring computation to the nearest square foot or acreage. Item 5 covers vertical relief — the surveyor must provide contour lines or spot elevations if selected. Item 6 addresses parking counts and striping for commercial properties. Item 7 concerns building square footage at ground level and requires dimensional measurements of buildings.\n\nItems 8 through 11 address utilities and site features in greater detail. Item 8 requires the surveyor to locate and identify underground utilities beyond what is visible. The surveyor must contact utility companies or retain a private utility locator, and the scope varies by sub-item. Item 9 covers wetlands boundaries as shown on government maps (though it does not require a wetlands delineation survey). Item 10 relates to reporting on striping or parking structures. Item 11 addresses zoning information and requires the surveyor to provide specific zoning details — this is one of the more complex and costly items because it requires zoning research and reporting setback requirements, allowable uses, and other zoning parameters.\n\nItems 12 through 20 cover additional specialized requirements. Item 12 involves exterior wall height measurements. Item 13 requires the surveyor to provide names of adjoining property owners obtained from current tax records. Item 14 addresses the location of wetlands survey flagging if a wetlands delineation has been performed by others. Items 15 through 17 deal with offsite easements and access, requiring the surveyor to trace and survey access routes and servient easements that benefit the subject property. Item 18 relates to professional liability insurance requirements. Item 19 addresses providing an electronic CAD file of the survey. Item 20 concerns the location of aboveground improvements on easement areas.\n\nCommonly requested items in typical commercial transactions include Items 1, 2, 3, 4, 6, 8, 11, 13, and 19. Items 5 (vertical relief), 15-17 (offsite easements), and 14 (wetlands flagging) are less frequently requested and tend to add significant cost and time to the survey. The surveyor should discuss Table A items with the client early in the engagement because each selected item affects the scope, timeline, and fee.',
