        id: 'fs-std-alta-s3',
        type: 'concept',
        title: 'Key Requirements: Tolerances, Depiction, and Certification',
        content: 'The 2021 ALTA/NSPS standards establish a Relative Positional Precision (RPP) of 2 centimeters (0.07 feet) plus 50 parts per million (ppm) as the maximum allowable tolerance. This means that the relative position of any point on the survey — boundaries, improvements, easements, or other features — must be accurate to within this tolerance. The RPP replaces the older "positional uncertainty" language and is measured at the 95% confidence level. For a typical urban lot of 200 feet, the allowable positional tolerance would be approximately 0.07 + (200 x 0.00005) = 0.08 feet. For a larger rural parcel of 5,000 feet across, the tolerance increases to 0.07 + (5,000 x 0.00005) = 0.32 feet. Understanding how RPP scales with distance is important for exam calculations.\n\nThe surveyor must show evidence of utilities observed during the fieldwork. This includes visible utility features such as manholes, valve boxes, hydrants, utility poles, transformers, pedestals, meters, junction boxes, and overhead wires. The surveyor is not required to determine the ownership or nature of underground utilities unless Table A Item 8 is selected. However, any visible evidence of underground utilities — such as pipeline markers, vent pipes, or warning signs — must be shown on the survey.\n\nAll improvements on the property must be located and shown on the survey, including buildings, fences, walls, driveways, parking areas, swimming pools, patios, and other significant structures. The surveyor must show the relationship between improvements and boundary lines (setback distances), between improvements and easement lines, and between improvements and rights of way. Any encroachments — where improvements from the subject property cross onto adjacent property, or where adjacent improvements cross onto the subject property — must be identified and noted.\n\nEasements and rights of way disclosed in the title commitment must be plotted on the survey to the extent they can be located from the recorded documents. Blanket easements (those that encumber the entire property without a defined location) should be noted but cannot be plotted. The surveyor must show the width, location, and recording information for each easement. Any improvements or encroachments within easement areas must be identified.\n\nThe certification is a formal statement by the surveyor that the survey was prepared in accordance with the ALTA/NSPS standards and that it meets the minimum requirements. The certification must name the parties to whom the survey is certified, which typically includes the buyer, the lender, the title company, and sometimes attorneys. The certification language must be consistent with Section 5 of the standards. On the face of the survey plat, the surveyor must include a legal description, a north arrow, a scale, a legend explaining symbols, the date of fieldwork, the surveyor\'s signature and seal, and notes addressing any exceptions or additional information required by the standards.',
