        content: 'The FEMA Elevation Certificate (EC) is a standardized form used to document the elevation of a building relative to the Base Flood Elevation (BFE) in a flood-prone area. The form is administered by the Federal Emergency Management Agency (FEMA) and is a critical component of the National Flood Insurance Program (NFIP). The NFIP was created by Congress in 1968 to make flood insurance available to property owners in communities that adopt and enforce floodplain management regulations. Without the NFIP, most property owners would be unable to obtain flood insurance because private insurers generally consider flood risk too concentrated and catastrophic to underwrite.\n\nThe primary purpose of the Elevation Certificate is to provide the elevation data needed to determine the proper flood insurance premium for a building. Insurance rates under the NFIP are based largely on the relationship between a building\'s lowest floor elevation and the BFE — the elevation that floodwater is expected to reach during a base flood event (a flood with a 1% annual chance of occurrence, commonly called the "100-year flood"). Buildings with their lowest floor above the BFE pay lower premiums; buildings below the BFE pay significantly higher premiums. The greater the difference between the lowest floor and the BFE, the greater the impact on the insurance rate.\n\nElevation Certificates are required in several situations. New construction and substantial improvements to existing buildings in Special Flood Hazard Areas (SFHAs) must have an EC completed to demonstrate compliance with local floodplain ordinances. Property owners seeking to reduce their flood insurance premiums may obtain an EC to document that their building\'s elevation is higher than previously assumed. Communities participating in the NFIP\'s Community Rating System (CRS) may require ECs for all buildings in the floodplain to earn premium discounts for their residents.\n\nThe Elevation Certificate must be completed by a licensed land surveyor, professional engineer, or architect who is authorized by law to certify elevation information. In most states, the surveyor performs the fieldwork to determine building elevations and completes Sections A through D of the form. The local community\'s floodplain administrator completes Section E (Building Eligibility) and Section F (Community Information). The insurance company or its agent uses the completed EC to calculate the flood insurance premium.\n\nThe current version of the Elevation Certificate form is the FEMA Form 086-0-33, which was last significantly revised in 2022. During the FS exam, you may be asked about the sections of the form, the datum requirements, or how flood zone designations affect the information required on the certificate. The form itself may be available as a reference document during the exam, so familiarity with its layout will help you navigate questions quickly.',
